History and Trivia:

-------------------


The Apple IIc Plus unit was a direct response to the Laser 128EX/2.


Apple retrofitted the IIc design to try to compete with Video Technology's high-speed Apple II 
clone. The retrofitting is evident in the design of the motherboard. The motherboard runs at 1MHz, 
unlike the Laser 128EX/2. In order to run its programs faster, Apple used a 4MHz 65C02 with 8k 
of high speed SRAM cache and licensed the accelerator design from Zip Technologies (makers of 
the ZipChip accelerator for the IIe and IIc). They built an accelerator into a 1MHz motherboard 
rather than designing a faster motherboard from scratch.


The designers of the Apple IIc Plus originally wanted to make a portable IIGS. Apple's management, 
bent on promoting the Mac, balked at the idea. At the same time, the Laser 128EX/2 made a quick 
design cycle mandatory. The result was an updated IIc.


The Apple IIc Plus was the finest Apple 8-bit computer ever built, but due to a lack of marketing, 
the apparent backward step in technology compared to the 16-bit Apple IIGS, and the aggressive 
sales of the Laser 128EX/2, the IIc Plus also was to be the most short-lived of the Apple II models. 


